:"1525–1554","1480–Male":"1480–Overleden","1481–Female":"1481–Overleden","1550":"1550","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","11 August 1549":"11 augustus 1549","1525":"1525","1624":"1624","1502":"1502","1522":"1522","1521":"1521","1554":"1554","about 1501":"circa 1501","1496":"1496","1549":"1549","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Pembroke Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembroke Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales","England":"England","Gloucestershire,England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"en":{"1502–1549":"1502–1549","1496–1550":"1496–1550","1522–1624":"1522–1624","1525–1554":"1525–1554","1480–Male":"1480–Deceased","1481–Female":"1481–Deceased","1550":"1550","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","11 August 1549":"11 August 1549","1525":"1525","1624":"1624","1502":"1502","1522":"1522","1521":"1521","1554":"1554","about 1501":"about 1501","1496":"1496","1549":"1549","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Pembroke Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembroke Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales","England":"England","Gloucestershire,England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Griffin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Gruffin, Griffin</i>, a pet form of Middle Welsh <i>Gruffudd</i>. In the Welsh border counties this name was introduced directly from Welsh, and in the eastern counties of England by Bretons from France who came over with the Norman conquest.","Irish: Anglicized (part translated) form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Gríobhtha</i>’, a personal name from <i>gríobh</i> ‘gryphon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffing","meanings":["Variant of   Griffin  ."]},{"name":"Griffee","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> (see   Griffin  )."]},{"name":"Griffy","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> (see   Griffin  )."]},{"name":"Griffey","meanings":["Irish (Clare): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> (see   Griffin  )."]},{"name":"Griffen","meanings":["Irish (Cork): variant of   Griffin  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]},{"name":"Rose","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Ostensibly from the vocabulary word denoting the flower (Latin <i>rosa</i>). However, the name was in use throughout the Middle Ages, long before any of the other girls' names derived from flowers, which are generally of 19th-century origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Elizabeth Rose Griffin was born in 1502, in Pembroke Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales, her father, Tristram Carfinkle, was 22 and her mother, Elizabeth Rose, was 22. She married Nicolas Tristram de Court Thomas in 1521, in Surrey, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1549, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1502–1549":"1502–1549","1496–1550":"1496–1550","1522–1624":"1522–1624","1525–1554":"1525–1554","1480–Male":"1480–Surnud","1481–Female":"1481–Surnud","1550":"1550","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","11 August 1549":"11. august 1549","1525":"1525","1624":"1624","1502":"1502","1522":"1522","1521":"1521","1554":"1554","about 1501":"umbes 1501","1496":"1496","1549":"1549","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Pembroke Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembroke Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales","England":"England","Gloucestershire,England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1502–1549":"1502–1549","1496–1550":"1496–1550","1522–1624":"1522–1624","1525–1554":"1525–1554","1480–Male":"1480–Kuollut","1481–Female":"1481–Kuollut","1550":"1550","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","11 August 1549":"11. elokuuta 1549","1525":"1525","1624":"1624","1502":"1502","1522":"1522","1521":"1521","1554":"1554","about 1501":"noin 1501","1496":"1496","1549":"1549","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Pembroke Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembroke Castle, Pembrokesh